    <p>The <strong>control plane</strong> is a Rails application that handles authentication, release publishing, environment management, and rollout sequencing. It decides what should run where.</p>

    <p><strong>GCP infrastructure</strong> handles delivery. Cloud Storage holds signed deployment specs. Artifact Registry holds Docker images. Secret Manager holds runtime secrets. Cloud KMS provides HSM-backed signing. Workload Identity Federation gives agents short-lived, scoped credentials without storing any GCP keys on your servers.</p>

    <p><strong>Your servers</strong> run the devopsellence agent, which periodically polls Cloud Storage for desired state, verifies cryptographic signatures, pulls images from Artifact Registry, resolves secrets from Secret Manager, and reconciles containers with zero-downtime rollouts via an Envoy proxy.</p>

    <h2>Why not store everything in the database?</h2>

    <p>A simpler architecture would keep secrets as encrypted columns, deploy state as JSON rows, and images behind a self-hosted registry. This works. Many platforms ship this way. But it creates three problems that compound as you scale:</p>

    <p><strong>Security.</strong> Secrets in a database are readable by anyone with database access &mdash; developers with console access, ops with backup access, anyone who exploits an SQL injection. You can encrypt at rest, but then you need to manage encryption keys, implement column-level access control, and build your own audit trail. GCP Secret Manager gives you all of this natively: IAM-scoped access, automatic encryption, key rotation, and Cloud Audit Logs for every access.</p>

    <p><strong>Scalability.</strong> If every agent polls the control plane for desired state at a frequent interval, you create a linear relationship between fleet size and control plane load. Cloud Storage is a globally distributed, CDN-backed object store designed for exactly this read pattern &mdash; agents poll GCS directly, not the control plane.</p>

    <p><strong>Resilience.</strong> If the control plane is both coordinator and delivery mechanism, any outage immediately affects all running applications. By delegating delivery to GCP, the control plane becomes something that can fail without cascading to your users. Agents continue serving traffic from cached GCS state, already-injected secrets, and already-pulled images.</p>

